Rating: 4
I loved this!! We have a beer can chicken cooker - If you don't have one, you have to try it! It cooks a whole chicken on the grill to perfection. I save the carcass and when I had 4 of them, I boiled them to make the broth, with some carrots, onion, celery, thyme and rosemary. I strained this and chilled the broth, then skimmed the fat. I picked all the meat off the bones, and came up with plenty to add to the soup at the end. Other than this, I followed the recipe pretty closely, leaving the soup in the blender until it was nearly smooth.

Rating: 4
Very good soup. Followed the recipe with ground ginger (1 1/2 tsp) and pureed with hand held blender. Had no chicken so I put in a rinsed can of cannelini beans, no corn. It was very, very tasty. I would definitely do this again chicken or no chicken.

Rating: 4
I wouldn't call it bland. I may have used twice the ginger but I didn't measure. It has a bright ginger flavor. I used homemade chicken broth that I had just prepared. My yam was giant and my russet potato was small. I used frozen broccoli but fresh corn. I only had about 3/4 cup of corn kernels from one ear. I added a parsnip for one of the carrots.

Rating: 3
I agree, I used this recipe mostly as a base- I think chicken soup is kind of a personal thing so I prefer to doctor it to my taste. I was drawn to the recipe because of the use of ginger- a nice idea, especially if you're under the weather. But for me the corn flavor was too strong, so I have since made it with squash and liked the flavor better. Also I like some substance in my chicken soup, so I turned it into a chicken noodle soup by adding wide egg noodles.

Rating: 3
This is a nice soup. I wouldn't follow the recipe though. It's more of a guide, IMO. First off, I wouldn't throw raw onions into a simmering broth and expect too much flavor.

